            "title": "Concept for a multi-modal endoscopic imaging system",
            "abstract": "Abstract: Requiring the involvement of a pathology laboratory, biopsy is a cumbersome and costly procedure. Its most promising alternative, optical biopsy, refers to a collection of endoscopic imaging techniques that allow cellular level histopathological observations to be performed on site. Regardless of the target pathology, however, optical imaging methods are yet to attain the selectivity and specificity of traditional histology. This is why multi-modal imaging, which can provide complete tissue characterization through complementary modalities, will be the key to the success of optical histology.<br><br>This work presents a new approach to realize ultra-miniaturized imaging systems that can support multiple imaging techniques and, hence, multi-modal endoscopy. In contrast to conventional designs, the probes presented here are built bottom-up from a silicon based micro-optical construction-kit. Through micro-fabrication this silicon optical bench technology (SiOB) provides a means to construct micro-parts with 3D features (undercuts, buried cavities, vias) through bonding of structured silicon wafers. The combination of 3D design possibilities and very high precision allows the creation of highly integrated endoscopic probes.<br><br>Three different prototypes of silicon based endoscopic probes highlight the inher-ent design possibilities of the silicon mechanics. Through the integration of a variety of reflective, refractive and diffractive optical components the probes showcase the support of multiple full-field and scanning imaging modalities such as white light microscopy, laser scanning fluorescence imaging and optical coherence tomography, all of which can be combined to form bimodal imaging systems. In spite of their small cross-section of only 2\u00d72.76mm2 the probes can also be outfitted with tunable optics, which facilitates the implementation of zoom optics",
